The band gaps of CDs and ZrCDs were calculated based on plots of (αhv)1/2 versus hv of CDs (Fig. 7
                        a) and ZrCDs (Fig. 7b) and listed in Tables S1 and S2. The calculated band gaps of CD1 to CD6 decrease gradually, which is 2.18, 2.06, 1.94, 1.82, 1.67 and 1.56 eV, respectively (Table S1). The intermolecular interactions between closely adjacent CDs become stronger as the concentration increases, resulting in a decrease in the energy gap (Scheme 2
                        ), which ultimately leads to PL red shift. On the contrary, the band gap of ZrCD1 to ZrCD6 (Table S2) holds steady at 2.23, 2.22, 2.22, 2.21, 2.19 and 2.18 eV, respectively. The existence of zirconium carboxylate prevents ZrCDs from aggregation at a certain concentration, keeps the band gap unchanged (Scheme 2) and suppresses the red shift of emission (Fig. 7c) [49–51].
